Gnarly JSON to DataFrames in 2 simple steps

Living in a JSON World

Being R people, we like data. We like to get our hands on data. The internet is a great series of tubes particularly suited to getting you data. People wanted to be able to consume data in a standard format, and when the dust settled, JSON seemed to be the winner. So we gotta deal.

Often, data we want is rectangular, or table-like. We often have to wrangle the data from JSON into something that can be table-like. Along the way, we have to either get rid of parts that don’t turn into rectangular data so easily, or somehow wrestle it into a rectangle.

Data Pretty Close to Rectangular

The following data is pretty close to rectangular. It is an array of objects. Each object has the same keynames throughout. So you can think of this structure as each object containing a row of data, and each keyname being a column.

This data is in simple-character-list.json. Note that I am not just outputting the raw file here, but converting to an R object and then back to JSON in a pretty format, because it is easier to do. But the result is the same.

jsonSimpleChar_lst <-
    read_json(here::here("dat", "simple-character-list.json"))

jsonSimpleChar_lst %>%

How do We Get This into a Dataframe?

Can I just try casting to a tibble? You’d think, and sometimes it works, but no, not here.

So, it’s a list of lists.

Turns out, you can get close if you transpose this list and then use as_tibble():

… But that’s all pretty ad hoc, and is fragile. There are more regular ways that are more widely applicable.

jsonSimpleChar_lst %>%
  transpose() %>%
  toJSON(auto_unbox = TRUE, pretty=TRUE)

The tidyr Package and Rectangling

There is a consistent way to turn weird, semi-rectangular structures into dataframes. Let’s just start by doing it with the tools from the tidyr package.

Let’s do this in steps:

tibble(obj = jsonSimpleChar_lst) %>%
    print(n=3)
## # A tibble: 20 x 1
##   obj             
##   <list>          
## 1 <named list [3]>
## 2 <named list [3]>
## 3 <named list [3]>
## # ... with 17 more rows

then:

tibble(obj = jsonSimpleChar_lst) %>%
    unnest_wider(obj) %>%
    print(n=3)
## # A tibble: 20 x 3
##      id name               title            
##   <int> <chr>              <chr>            
## 1     0 Daenerys Targaryen Mother of Dragons
## 2     1 Samwell Tarly      Maester          
## 3     2 Jon Snow           King of the North
## # ... with 17 more rows

What Just Happened?

With the tibble(obj = jsonSimpleChar_lst) statement, we made obj a list-column, or a column in a tibble whose values are lists. So it is a list of lists.

Then we called unnest_wider(obj), whose first argument, with the %>% operator, is actually the first tibble we made. unnest_wider() then looks at the column obj, and says, “Well, each row is a list of key value pairs. I can turn the keys into column names and values into the data entries. And do it consistently across all of the rows.” Which it does, and boom, you have a tibble like you want.

Other tricks

You can use hoist() to just pull out any particular key that you want, like name. When it does this, by default, it removes it from the obj list once it is made into its own column.

tibble(obj = jsonSimpleChar_lst) %>%
    hoist(obj, "name") %>%
    print(n=3)
## # A tibble: 20 x 2
##   name               obj             
##   <chr>              <list>          
## 1 Daenerys Targaryen <named list [2]>
## 2 Samwell Tarly      <named list [2]>
## 3 Jon Snow           <named list [2]>
## # ... with 17 more rows

What happens if you unnest_longer() instead?

tibble(obj = jsonSimpleChar_lst) %>%
    unnest_longer(obj) %>%
    print(n=7)
## # A tibble: 60 x 2
##   obj          obj_id
##   <named list> <chr> 
## 1 <int [1]>    id    
## 2 <chr [1]>    name  
## 3 <chr [1]>    title 
## 4 <int [1]>    id    
## 5 <chr [1]>    name  
## 6 <chr [1]>    title 
## 7 <int [1]>    id    
## # ... with 53 more rows

You can see that you get a result, but the obj column now has a list-column, but each row can have a different type. It isn’t really what we want here, but it will be useful in other cases.

A more complex example.

But this doesn’t really pay off in the simple example, since we’ve shown at the start some shortcuts that don’t require doing hoisting and unnesting. Let’s look at a gnarly example.

jsonComplex_lst <-
    read_json(here::here("dat", "complex-json.json"))

#listviewer::jsonedit(jsonComplex_lst)

listviewer::jsonedit() is key for gnarly JSON

There’s a lot going on here. Too much to explain. But it is a real life example that I had to recently sort through to get information from a bunch of files like this to compare across them.

I’m not going to explain it all. Instead, I am going to give a sequence of unnest/hoist calls that got out the data under parameters. There are 6 parameters, each of which is a time series of values. I want those 6 parameters in dataframes that I can stitch together to inspect.

Let’s go down a rabbit hole.

parameters_df <-
  tibble(obj=jsonComplex_lst) %>%
  filter(names(obj) == "data") %>%
  unnest_longer(obj) %>%
  unnest_wider(obj) %>%
  select(tisObjectId, parameters) %>%
  unnest_longer(parameters) %>%
  unnest_wider(parameters) %>%
  select(tisObjectId, parameterName=name, values) %>%
  unnest_longer(values) %>%
  unnest_wider(values) %>%
  mutate(value = unlist(value)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = "parameterName", values_from = "value")
